{"title_page": "Arvind Krishna", "text_new": "{{about|the IBM executive|other uses}}\n{{Use American English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|Indian American business executive and CEO of IBM}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image       = Arvind Krishna.jpg.png\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = Arvind Krishna\n| birth_date  = {{Birth year and age|1962}}\n| birth_place = [[West Godavari, Andhra Pradesh]], India<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|title=Arvind Krishna ascends beyond cloud at IBM|url=https://tech.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/corporate/arvind-krishna-ascends-beyond-cloud-at-ibm/73825286|publisher=Economic Times|accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Meet Arvind Krishna, new IBM CEO who is the latest Indian to head a global IT company|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/technology/news/story/meet-arvind-krishna-new-ibm-ceo-who-is-latest-south-indian-to-head-global-it-company-1642327-2020-02-01|publisher=India Today|accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref>\n| death_date  = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place = \n| other_names = \n| spouse      = \n| children    = \n| education   = [[IIT Kanpur]] ([[B.Tech]])<br />[[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign]] ([[PhD]])\n| occupation  = \n| known_for   = \n| salary      = \n| title       = CEO of [[IBM]]\n| term        = \n| father      = Vijay Krishna\n| mother      = Aarti Krishna\n| predecessor = [[Ginni Rometty]]\n}}\n\n'''Arvind Krishna''' (born 1962) is an [[Indian Americans|Indian American]] business executive. He is the [[chief executive officer]] (CEO) of [[IBM]].<ref>{{cite news|title=IBM names Indian-origin Arvind Krishna as CEO|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/technology/in-other-news/310120/ibm-names-indian-origin-arvind-krishna-as-ceo.html|publisher=Deccan Chronicle|accessdate=31 January 2020}}</ref> Krishna began his career at IBM as an engineer, was promoted to [[senior vice president]] in 2015, and was promoted to CEO in 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://fortune.com/2020/02/03/ibm-ceo-arvind-krishna-what-you-need-to-know/|title=What you need to know about new IBM CEO Arvind Krishna|publisher=Fortune|accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref> He led IBM's 2018 acquisition of [[Red Hat]] for $34 billion, which is the largest software company acquisition in history.<ref name=\"red-hat\">{{cite web\n | url         = https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/30/ibm-ceo-ginni-rometty-steps-down-arvind-krishna-to-take-over.html\n | title       = IBM CEO Ginni Rometty is stepping down, Arvind Krishna to take over\n | last        = Novet\n | first       = Jordan\n | date        = 2020-01-30\n | website     = CNBC\n | access-date = 2020-02-01\n | quote       = Krishna worked on the Red Hat acquisition.}}</ref> On his first day as CEO, Krishna wrote to IBM staff, \"I believe we can make IBM the most trusted technology partner of the 21st century...Character is of the utmost importance.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=My first day as CEO \u2014 our journey together|quote=I believe we can make IBM the most trusted technology partner of the 21st century.|url=https://fortune.com/2020/04/06/new-ibm-ceo-arvind-krishna-coronavirus-resilience|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nKrishna was born in [[West Godavari, Andhra Pradesh]], India.<ref name=\"auto\"/> His father, Major General Vijay Krishna,  was an army officer who worked for the [[Indian Army]] of the [[Government of India]] and his mother, Aarti Krishna, worked for the welfare of Army widows.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economictimes.com/news/company/corporate-trends/industry-leaders-peers-raise-a-toast-to-good-news/articleshow/73824893.cms|title=Industry leaders, peers raise a toast to good news|publisher=Economic Times|accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timesofindia.com/business/india-business/indian-origin-technologist-arvind-krishna-to-lead-ibm-joins-club-of-global-indian-ceos/articleshow/73819678.cms|title=Indian-origin technologist Arvind Krishna to lead IBM, joins club of global Indian CEOs|publisher=Times of India|accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe completed schooling in [[St Joseph's Academy (Dehradun)|St Joseph's Academy, Dehradun]] and  the [[Stanes School]], [[Coonoor, Tamil Nadu]], before receiving a bachelor's degree in [[electrical engineering]] from the [[Indian Institute of Technology, Kanpur]] in 1985.<ref name=\"auto\"/> He subsequently traveled to the United States to earn a [[PhD]] in electrical engineering from the [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign]] in 1990.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news\n | url         = https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/30/technology/ginni-rometty-ibm-ceo.html\n | title       = Ginni Rometty to Step Down as C.E.O. of IBM\n | last        = Lohr\n | first       = Steve\n | date        = 2020-01-30\n | work        = The New York Times\n | access-date = 2020-01-31\n | language    = en-US\n | issn        = 0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n | url          = https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/arvind-krishna-ibmer-who-joins-elite-indianorigin-ceos-club/1722319\n | title        = Arvind Krishna: IBMer who joins elite Indian-origin CEOs' club\n | last         = \n | first        = \n | date         = 2020-01-31\n | website      = outlookindia.com\n | url-status   = live\n | archive-url  = \n | archive-date = \n | access-date  = 2020-01-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=IITian Arvind Krishna appointed CEO of global tech giant IBM; 5 little known facts about him|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/story/iitian-arvind-krishna-appointed-ceo-of-global-tech-giant-ibm-5-little-known-facts-about-him-ginni-rometty/1/395024.html|publisher=Business Today|accessdate=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nKrishna joined IBM in 1990, rising to become senior vice president for IBM's cloud and cognitive software. He led IBM's 2018 acquisition of [[Red Hat]] for $34 billion. <ref name=\"red-hat\" />\n\nHe was appointed to become IBM CEO on January 31, 2020, succeeding [[Ginni Rometty]] who had served as CEO since 2012.<ref>{{cite news\n | url         = https://www.wsj.com/articles/ginni-rometty-stepping-down-as-ibm-ceo-11580420650\n | title       = Ginni Rometty Stepping Down as IBM CEO\n | last        = Chin\n | first       = Kimberly\n | date        = 2020-01-30\n | work        = Wall Street Journal\n | access-date = 2020-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n | url          = https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-30/ibm-names-arvind-krishna-as-ceo-rometty-to-retire-at-year-s-end\n | title        = IBM Names Arvind Krishna CEO, Replacing Ginni Rometty\n | last         = Carville\n | first        = Olivia\n | date         = 2020-01-30\n | website      = Bloomberg\n | url-status   = live\n | archive-url  = \n | archive-date = \n | access-date  = 2020-01-31}}</ref>\nHe joined [[Satya Nadella]], [[Sundar Pichai]], and [[Shantanu Narayen]] as an [[Indian Americans|Indian American]] [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] of a major [[United States]] technology company.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Twitter}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bus}}\n{{succession box\n| title  = [[List of IBM CEOs]]\n| before = [[Ginni Rometty]]\n| after  = Present CEO\n| years  = 1914\u2013present\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{IBM}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Krishna, Arvind}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:IBM employees]]\n[[Category:American computer businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American electrical engineers]]\n[[Category:American chief executives]]\n[[Category:American technology chief executives]]\n[[Category:American chief executives of Fortune 500 companies]]\n[[Category:American people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:IBM people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Telugu people]]\n[[Category:Engineers from Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Indian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Indian Institute of Technology Kanpur alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Andhra Pradesh]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the IBM executive|other uses}}\n{{Use American English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|Indian American business executive and CEO of IBM}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image       = [[File:Arvind Krishna.jpg.png|thumb]]\n<br />\n| alt         =\n| caption     =\n| birth_name  = Arvind Krishna\n| birth_date  = {{Birth year and age|1962}} \n| birth_place =[[West Godavari]], [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[India]]<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|title=Arvind Krishna ascends beyond cloud at IBM|url=https://tech.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/corporate/arvind-krishna-ascends-beyond-cloud-at-ibm/73825286|publisher=Economic Times|accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Meet Arvind Krishna, new IBM CEO who is the latest Indian to head a global IT company|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/technology/news/story/meet-arvind-krishna-new-ibm-ceo-who-is-latest-south-indian-to-head-global-it-company-1642327-2020-02-01|publisher=India Today|accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref>\n| death_date  = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place =\n| other_names =\n| spouse  = \n| children = \n| education   = [[IIT Kanpur]] ([[B.Tech]])<br />[[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign]] ([[PhD]])\n| occupation  = \n| known_for   = \n| salary      =\n| title       = CEO of [[IBM]]\n| term        =\n| father  = Vijay Krishna\n| mother  = Aarti Krishna\n| predecessor = [[Ginni Rometty]]\n}}\n\n'''Arvind Krishna''' (born 1962) is an [[Indian Americans|Indian American]] business executive. He is the [[chief executive officer]] (CEO) of [[IBM]].<ref>{{cite news|title=IBM names Indian-origin Arvind Krishna as CEO|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/technology/in-other-news/310120/ibm-names-indian-origin-arvind-krishna-as-ceo.html|publisher=Deccan Chronicle|accessdate=31 January 2020}}</ref> Krishna began his career at IBM as an engineer, was promoted to [[senior vice president]] in 2015, and was promoted to CEO in 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://fortune.com/2020/02/03/ibm-ceo-arvind-krishna-what-you-need-to-know/|title=What you need to know about new IBM CEO Arvind Krishna|publisher=Fortune|accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref> He led IBM's 2018 acquisition of [[Red Hat]] for $34 billion, which is the largest software company acquisition in history.<ref name=\"red-hat\">{{cite web\n | url          = https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/30/ibm-ceo-ginni-rometty-steps-down-arvind-krishna-to-take-over.html\n | title        = IBM CEO Ginni Rometty is stepping down, Arvind Krishna to take over\n | last         = Novet\n | first        = Jordan\n | date         = 2020-01-30\n | website      = CNBC\n | access-date  = 2020-02-01\n | quote        = Krishna worked on the Red Hat acquisition.}}</ref> On his first day as CEO, Krishna wrote to IBM staff, \"I believe we can make IBM the most trusted technology partner of the 21st century...Character is of the utmost importance.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=My first day as CEO \u2014 our journey together|quote=I believe we can make IBM the most trusted technology partner of the 21st century.|url=https://fortune.com/2020/04/06/new-ibm-ceo-arvind-krishna-coronavirus-resilience|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nKrishna was born in [[West Godavari]], [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[India]].<ref name=\"auto\"/> His father, Major General Vijay Krishna,  was an army officer who worked for the [[Indian Army]] of the [[Government of India]] and his mother, Aarti Krishna, worked for the welfare of Army widows.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economictimes.com/news/company/corporate-trends/industry-leaders-peers-raise-a-toast-to-good-news/articleshow/73824893.cms|title=Industry leaders, peers raise a toast to good news|publisher=Economic Times|accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timesofindia.com/business/india-business/indian-origin-technologist-arvind-krishna-to-lead-ibm-joins-club-of-global-indian-ceos/articleshow/73819678.cms|title=Indian-origin technologist Arvind Krishna to lead IBM, joins club of global Indian CEOs|publisher=Times of India|accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe completed schooling in [[St Joseph's Academy (Dehradun)|St Joseph's Academy, Dehradun]] and  the [[Stanes School]], [[Coonoor]], [[Tamil Nadu]], before receiving a bachelor's degree in [[electrical engineering]] from the [[Indian Institute of Technology, Kanpur]] in 1985.<ref name=\"auto\"/> He subsequently traveled to the [[United States]] to earn a [[PhD]] in electrical engineering from the [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign]] in 1990.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news\n | url         = https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/30/technology/ginni-rometty-ibm-ceo.html\n | title       = Ginni Rometty to Step Down as C.E.O. of IBM\n | last        = Lohr\n | first       = Steve\n | date        = 2020-01-30\n | work        = The New York Times\n | access-date = 2020-01-31\n | language    = en-US\n | issn        = 0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n | url          = https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/arvind-krishna-ibmer-who-joins-elite-indianorigin-ceos-club/1722319\n | title        = Arvind Krishna: IBMer who joins elite Indian-origin CEOs' club\n | last         =\n | first        =\n | date         = 2020-01-31\n | website      = outlookindia.com\n | url-status   = live\n | archive-url  =\n | archive-date =\n | access-date  = 2020-01-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=IITian Arvind Krishna appointed CEO of global tech giant IBM; 5 little known facts about him|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/story/iitian-arvind-krishna-appointed-ceo-of-global-tech-giant-ibm-5-little-known-facts-about-him-ginni-rometty/1/395024.html|publisher=Business Today|accessdate=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nKrishna joined IBM in 1990, rising to become senior vice president for IBM's cloud and cognitive software. He led IBM's 2018 acquisition of [[Red Hat]] for $34 billion. <ref name=\"red-hat\" />\n\nHe was appointed to become IBM CEO on January 31, 2020, succeeding [[Ginni Rometty]] who had served as CEO since 2012.<ref>{{cite news\n | url         = https://www.wsj.com/articles/ginni-rometty-stepping-down-as-ibm-ceo-11580420650\n | title       = Ginni Rometty Stepping Down as IBM CEO\n | last        = Chin\n | first       = Kimberly\n | date        = 2020-01-30\n | work        = Wall Street Journal\n | access-date = 2020-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n | url          = https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-30/ibm-names-arvind-krishna-as-ceo-rometty-to-retire-at-year-s-end\n | title        = IBM Names Arvind Krishna CEO, Replacing Ginni Rometty\n | last         = Carville\n | first        = Olivia\n | date         = 2020-01-30\n | website      = Bloomberg\n | url-status   = live\n | archive-url  =\n | archive-date =\n | access-date  = 2020-01-31}}</ref>\nHe joined [[Satya Nadella]], [[Sundar Pichai]], and [[Shantanu Narayen]] as an [[Indian Americans|Indian American]] [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] of a major [[United States]] technology company.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Twitter}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bus}}\n{{succession box\n| title  = [[List of IBM CEOs]]\n| before = [[Ginni Rometty]]\n| after  = Present CEO\n| years  = 1914\u2013present\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{IBM}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Krishna, Arvind}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:IBM employees]]\n[[Category:American computer businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American electrical engineers]]\n[[Category:American chief executives]]\n[[Category:American technology chief executives]]\n[[Category:American chief executives of Fortune 500 companies]]\n[[Category:American people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:IBM people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Telugu people]]\n[[Category:Engineers from Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Indian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Indian Institute of Technology Kanpur alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Andhra Pradesh]]\n", "name_user": "MB", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix infobox image syntax, overlinking", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arvind_Krishna"}
{"title_page": "Berg report", "text_new": "[[File:Accelerated Development in Sub-Saharan Africa.JPG|thumb|Cover of Accelerated Development in Sub-Saharan Africa, World Bank report published in 1981]]\n\nThe '''Berg report''' is the name most commonly used for the [[World Bank]]-published report \"Accelerated Development in Sub-Saharan Africa: A Plan for Action,\" written by Elliot Berg in 1981. The report was written in response to a 1979 request from the African Governors of the World Bank for a paper analyzing the development problems facing African countries. It also responds to a set of policies determined by African Chiefs of State in 1980, called the [[Lagos Plan of Action]]. While the Lagos Plan endorsed inward-looking policies of African self-reliance, the Berg report advocated for outward-looking policies of increased international trade.\n\n== Synopsis ==\nThe report is historically important for having marked a shift in African countries\u2019 economic policies towards [[economic liberalization]]. It details several policy recommendations in its plan for action, including \u201c(1) more suitable trade and exchange-rate policies; (2) increased efficiency of resource use in the public sector; and (3) improvement in agriculture policies.\u201d<ref>{{cite book|last1=Berg|first1=Elliot|title=Accelerated Development in Sub-Saharan Africa: An Agenda for Action|date=1981|publisher=International Bank for Reconstruction and Development / The World Bank|location=Washington, DC|page=5|url=http://www-wds.worldbank.org/external/default/WDSContentServer/IW3P/IB/2000/04/13/000178830_98101911444774/Rendered/PDF/multi_page.pdf|accessdate=13 March 2015}}</ref> In terms of trade and exchange-rate policies, the report recommends liberalizations including \u201ccorrection of overvalued exchange rates [\u2026]; improved price incentives for exports and for agriculture; lower and more uniform protection for industry; and reduced use of direct controls.\u201d<ref>{{cite book|last1=Berg|first1=Elliot|title=Accelerated Development in Sub-Saharan Africa: An Agenda for Action|date=1981|publisher=International Bank for Reconstruction and Development / The World Bank|location=Washington, DC|page=30|url=http://www-wds.worldbank.org/external/default/WDSContentServer/IW3P/IB/2000/04/13/000178830_98101911444774/Rendered/PDF/multi_page.pdf|accessdate=13 March 2015}}</ref> For efficient resource usage, the Berg report identifies government and parastatal agencies as being overextended, and suggests streamlining public services, in part by allowing a greater share of these to be provided by the private sector. In the area of agriculture, they propose promoting export of cash crops by reducing taxes and other unfavorable terms of trade, as well as making domestic food markets more efficient by loosening regulation and increasing the role of the private sector in inputs (such as fertilizer) and in marketing foodstuffs (e.g. deregulating food prices).<ref>{{cite book|last1=Berg|first1=Elliot|title=Accelerated Development in Sub-Saharan Africa: An Agenda for Action|date=1981|publisher=International Bank for Reconstruction and Development / The World Bank|location=Washington, DC|pages=61\u201369|url=http://www-wds.worldbank.org/external/default/WDSContentServer/IW3P/IB/2000/04/13/000178830_98101911444774/Rendered/PDF/multi_page.pdf|accessdate=13 March 2015}}</ref> The report concludes with a strong appeal to international aid organizations to support African governments as they shift towards the policies of economic liberalization recommended by the World Bank.\n\n== Reception ==\nThe recommendations contained in the World Bank's report held real significance for African political leaders, as the Bank is a major development lending agency with the power to affect the identification and design of development projects.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Howell|first1=John|title=Review: The World Bank. Accelerated Development in Sub-Saharan Africa: An Agenda for Action|journal=Economic Development and Cultural Change|date=April 1985|volume=33|issue=3|page=670|jstor=1153961}}</ref> [[Structural adjustment]] programs (SAPs) instituted by the World Bank made loans conditional on specific conditions, a strong inducement for countries to follow [[free-market]] policies. The report makes specific recommendations to donors, stating, \u201cThe level and pattern of donor assistance to a country must be determined in the framework of programs of action prepared by individual governments, which address the critical development policy issues outlined in this Report.\u201d<ref>{{cite book|last1=Berg|first1=Elliot|title=Accelerated Development in Sub-Saharan Africa: An Agenda for Action|date=1981|publisher=International Bank for Reconstruction and Development / The World Bank|location=Washington, DC|pages=124\u2013125|url=http://www-wds.worldbank.org/external/default/WDSContentServer/IW3P/IB/2000/04/13/000178830_98101911444774/Rendered/PDF/multi_page.pdf|accessdate=13 March 2015}}</ref> Explicitly advocating for \u201cpolicy action and foreign assistance that are mutually reinforcing,\u201d the report reinforces its own recommendations by leveraging loan and aid money.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Berg|first1=Elliot|title=Accelerated Development in Sub-Saharan Africa: An Agenda for Action|date=1981|publisher=International Bank for Reconstruction and Development / The World Bank|location=Washington, DC|page=133|url=http://www-wds.worldbank.org/external/default/WDSContentServer/IW3P/IB/2000/04/13/000178830_98101911444774/Rendered/PDF/multi_page.pdf|accessdate=13 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Loxley|first1=John|title=The Berg Report and the Model of Accumulation in Sub-Saharan Africa|journal=Review of African Political Economy|date=1983|volume=27/28|page=202|jstor=4005615}}</ref> \nThe Berg report generated criticism from some scholars of international development and African studies, particularly for the way it represents \u201cthe balance of responsibility for development failure.\u201d<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Howell|first1=John|title=Review: The World Bank. Accelerated Development in Sub-Saharan Africa: An Agenda for Action|journal=Economic Development and Cultural Change|date=April 1985|volume=33|issue=3|page=669|jstor=1153961}}</ref> The report prioritizes \u201cdomestic policy inadequacies\u201d as a major cause for under-performing economies, and some have argued that the report downplays \u201cthe importance of external factors in shaping policy and performance in Sub-Saharan Africa.\u201d<ref>{{cite book|last1=Berg|first1=Elliot|title=Accelerated Development in Sub-Saharan Africa: An Agenda for Action|date=1981|publisher=International Bank for Reconstruction and Development / The World Bank|location=Washington, DC|page=4|url=http://www-wds.worldbank.org/external/default/WDSContentServer/IW3P/IB/2000/04/13/000178830_98101911444774/Rendered/PDF/multi_page.pdf|accessdate=13 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Loxley|first1=John|title=The Berg Report and the Model of Accumulation in Sub-Saharan Africa|journal=Review of African Political Economy|date=1983|volume=27/28|page=199|jstor=4005615}}</ref> In 1981, when the report was published, an important external factor was the instability of the global economy, particularly the [[stagflation]] of the 1970s, and the [[1979 energy crisis]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Lagos plan of action]]\n* [[Washington consensus]]\n* [[Trade liberalization]]\n* [[Globalization]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://econ.worldbank.org/external/default/main?pagePK=64165259&theSitePK=469072&piPK=64165421&menuPK=64166093&entityID=000178830_98101911444774 Full PDF version of \"Accelerated development in sub-Saharan Africa: an agenda for action\"]\n* [http://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/53385/gail-m-gerhart/accelerated-development-in-sub-saharan-africa-an-agenda-for-acti Review of Berg report by ''Foreign Affairs'']\n* [http://www.historyandtheheadlines.abc-clio.com/ContentPages/ContentPage.aspx?entryId=1161862&currentSection=1130228 Summary of Berg report from ABC CLIO's \"History and the Headlines\"]\n* [http://www.africaresearchinstitute.org/publications/k-y-amoako/ Interview with K.Y. Amoako, the only African co-author of the Berg report]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berg Report}}\n[[Category:World Bank]]\n[[Category:1981 documents]]\n[[Category:1981 in Africa]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Accelerated Development in Sub-Saharan Africa.JPG|thumb|Cover of Accelerated Development in Sub-Saharan Africa, World Bank report published in 1981]]\n\nThe '''Berg report''' is the name most commonly used for the [[World Bank]]-published report \"Accelerated Development in Sub-Saharan Africa: A Plan for Action,\" written by Elliot Berg in 1981. The report was written in response to a 1979 request from the African Governors of the World Bank for a paper analyzing the development problems facing African countries. It also responds to a set of policies determined by African Chiefs of State in 1980, called the [[Lagos Plan of Action]]. While the Lagos Plan endorsed inward-looking policies of African self-reliance, the Berg report advocated for outward-looking policies of increased international trade.\n\n== Synopsis ==\nThe report is historically important for having marked a shift in African countries\u2019 economic policies towards [[economic liberalization]]. It details several policy recommendations in its plan for action, including \u201c(1) more suitable trade and exchange-rate policies; (2) increased efficiency of resource use in the public sector; and (3) improvement in agriculture policies.\u201d<ref>{{cite book|last1=Berg|first1=Elliot|title=Accelerated Development in Sub-Saharan Africa: An Agenda for Action|date=1981|publisher=International Bank for Reconstruction and Development / The World Bank|location=Washington, DC|page=5|url=http://www-wds.worldbank.org/external/default/WDSContentServer/IW3P/IB/2000/04/13/000178830_98101911444774/Rendered/PDF/multi_page.pdf|accessdate=13 March 2015}}</ref> In terms of trade and exchange-rate policies, the report recommends liberalizations including \u201ccorrection of overvalued exchange rates [\u2026]; improved price incentives for exports and for agriculture; lower and more uniform protection for industry; and reduced use of direct controls.\u201d<ref>{{cite book|last1=Berg|first1=Elliot|title=Accelerated Development in Sub-Saharan Africa: An Agenda for Action|date=1981|publisher=International Bank for Reconstruction and Development / The World Bank|location=Washington, DC|page=30|url=http://www-wds.worldbank.org/external/default/WDSContentServer/IW3P/IB/2000/04/13/000178830_98101911444774/Rendered/PDF/multi_page.pdf|accessdate=13 March 2015}}</ref> For efficient resource usage, the Berg report identifies government and parastatal agencies as being overextended, and suggests streamlining public services, in part by allowing a greater share of these to be provided by the private sector. In the area of agriculture, they propose promoting export of cash crops by reducing taxes and other unfavorable terms of trade, as well as making domestic food markets more efficient by loosening regulation and increasing the role of the private sector in inputs (such as fertilizer) and in marketing foodstuffs (e.g. deregulating food prices).<ref>{{cite book|last1=Berg|first1=Elliot|title=Accelerated Development in Sub-Saharan Africa: An Agenda for Action|date=1981|publisher=International Bank for Reconstruction and Development / The World Bank|location=Washington, DC|pages=61\u201369|url=http://www-wds.worldbank.org/external/default/WDSContentServer/IW3P/IB/2000/04/13/000178830_98101911444774/Rendered/PDF/multi_page.pdf|accessdate=13 March 2015}}</ref> The report concludes with a strong appeal to international aid organizations to support African governments as they shift towards the policies of economic liberalization recommended by the World Bank.\n\n== Reception ==\nThe recommendations contained in the World Bank\u2019s report held real significance for African political leaders, as the Bank is a major development lending agency with the power to affect the identification and design of development projects.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Howell|first1=John|title=Review: The World Bank. Accelerated Development in Sub-Saharan Africa: An Agenda for Action|journal=Economic Development and Cultural Change|date=April 1985|volume=33|issue=3|page=670|jstor=1153961}}</ref> [[Structural adjustment]] programs (SAPs) instituted by the World Bank made loans conditional on specific conditions, a strong inducement for countries to follow [[free-market]] policies. The report makes specific recommendations to donors, stating, \u201cThe level and pattern of donor assistance to a country must be determined in the framework of programs of action prepared by individual governments, which address the critical development policy issues outlined in this Report.\u201d<ref>{{cite book|last1=Berg|first1=Elliot|title=Accelerated Development in Sub-Saharan Africa: An Agenda for Action|date=1981|publisher=International Bank for Reconstruction and Development / The World Bank|location=Washington, DC|pages=124\u2013125|url=http://www-wds.worldbank.org/external/default/WDSContentServer/IW3P/IB/2000/04/13/000178830_98101911444774/Rendered/PDF/multi_page.pdf|accessdate=13 March 2015}}</ref> Explicitly advocating for \u201cpolicy action and foreign assistance that are mutually reinforcing,\u201d the report reinforces its own recommendations by leveraging loan and aid money.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Berg|first1=Elliot|title=Accelerated Development in Sub-Saharan Africa: An Agenda for Action|date=1981|publisher=International Bank for Reconstruction and Development / The World Bank|location=Washington, DC|page=133|url=http://www-wds.worldbank.org/external/default/WDSContentServer/IW3P/IB/2000/04/13/000178830_98101911444774/Rendered/PDF/multi_page.pdf|accessdate=13 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Loxley|first1=John|title=The Berg Report and the Model of Accumulation in Sub-Saharan Africa|journal=Review of African Political Economy|date=1983|volume=27/28|page=202|jstor=4005615}}</ref> \nThe Berg report generated criticism from some scholars of international development and African studies, particularly for the way it represents \u201cthe balance of responsibility for development failure.\u201d<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Howell|first1=John|title=Review: The World Bank. Accelerated Development in Sub-Saharan Africa: An Agenda for Action|journal=Economic Development and Cultural Change|date=April 1985|volume=33|issue=3|page=669|jstor=1153961}}</ref> The report prioritizes \u201cdomestic policy inadequacies\u201d as a major cause for under-performing economies, and some have argued that the report downplays \u201cthe importance of external factors in shaping policy and performance in Sub-Saharan Africa.\u201d<ref>{{cite book|last1=Berg|first1=Elliot|title=Accelerated Development in Sub-Saharan Africa: An Agenda for Action|date=1981|publisher=International Bank for Reconstruction and Development / The World Bank|location=Washington, DC|page=4|url=http://www-wds.worldbank.org/external/default/WDSContentServer/IW3P/IB/2000/04/13/000178830_98101911444774/Rendered/PDF/multi_page.pdf|accessdate=13 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Loxley|first1=John|title=The Berg Report and the Model of Accumulation in Sub-Saharan Africa|journal=Review of African Political Economy|date=1983|volume=27/28|page=199|jstor=4005615}}</ref> In 1981, when the report was published, an important external factor was the instability of the global economy, particularly the [[stagflation]] of the 1970s, and the [[1979 energy crisis]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Lagos plan of action]]\n* [[Washington consensus]]\n* [[Trade liberalization]]\n* [[Globalization]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://econ.worldbank.org/external/default/main?pagePK=64165259&theSitePK=469072&piPK=64165421&menuPK=64166093&entityID=000178830_98101911444774 Full PDF version of \"Accelerated development in sub-Saharan Africa: an agenda for action\"]\n* [http://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/53385/gail-m-gerhart/accelerated-development-in-sub-saharan-africa-an-agenda-for-acti Review of Berg report by ''Foreign Affairs'']\n* [http://www.historyandtheheadlines.abc-clio.com/ContentPages/ContentPage.aspx?entryId=1161862&currentSection=1130228 Summary of Berg report from ABC CLIO's \"History and the Headlines\"]\n* [http://www.africaresearchinstitute.org/publications/k-y-amoako/ Interview with K.Y. Amoako, the only African co-author of the Berg report]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berg Report}}\n[[Category:World Bank]]\n[[Category:1981 documents]]\n[[Category:1981 in Africa]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReception:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Berg_report"}
{"title_page": "Pirate Party Romania", "text_new": "{{Infobox political party\n| name = Pirate Party Romania\n| native_name = Partidul Pirat Romania\n| logo = RomaniaPirateParty March2020.svg\n| logo_size = 200px\n| colorcode = #0000FF\n| foundation = 2009\n| ideology = [[Pirate Party|Pirate politics]]<br>\n[[Freedom of Information]]<br>\n[[Privacy]]<br>\n[[Distributism]]<br>\n[[Open government|Transparency of government]]\n| international = [[Pirate Parties International]]\n| website = [http://partidulpirat.ro/ www.partidulpirat.ro]\n}}\n\nThe ''' Pirate Party Romania''' ({{lang-ro|Partidul Pirat Rom\u00e2nia}}) is a [[political party]] in [[Romania]] based on the Swedish [[Pirate Party (Sweden)|Pirate Party]].  The party was a member of the [[Pirate Parties International|international Pirate Party movement]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pp-international.net/node/11 |title=PPI Members |publisher=PP-International |accessdate=2009-12-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100529031446/http://www.pp-international.net/node/11 |archivedate=2010-05-29 }}</ref> and is focused on copyright and patent reform, internet freedom, and government transparency.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.capital.ro/articol/update-pachetul-telecom-imposibil-de-implementat-in-forma-sa-actuala-125212.html |title=Telecom Package, impossible to implement in current state  |publisher=Capital |accessdate=2009-12-10|language=ro}}</ref>\n\nThe website of the Romanian Pirate Party was launched on 9 June 2009, and the first online meeting was held on 19 July 2009. The same year, on 6 August, members held their first live meeting, while one month later, on 7 September, the first article regarding the party was published in the Romanian online media.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.realitatea.net/partidul-piratilor-din-romania-se-va-infiinta-in-jumatate-de-an_608577.html |title=Romanian Pirate Party will be established in six months  |publisher=Realitatea TV |accessdate=2009-12-10|language=ro}}</ref>\n\n==Party registration==\n\nIn preparation for the official registration the party statute was approved by the founding members, and the first elected board was composed of Cristian Bulumac (President), \u015etefan Marius Angelescu (Vice-President), Claudiu Marginean (Founding President), \u0218tefan Cristian Br\u00eendu\u0219\u0103 (General Secretary) until March 2020, with a few exceptions.\n\nOn 11 February 2014 the party has submitted to the authorities the official request to be legally registered as a political party without the required signatures of 25,000 founding members.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vice.com/ro/read/piratii-ataca-legea-partidelor-la-curtea-constitutionala |title=Pirates attack the law at the Constitutional Court  |publisher=Vice.com/ro |accessdate=2014-02-14|language=ro}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2015, the Pirate Party contested the electoral law at the [[Constitutional Court of Romania]], arguing that the law violates [[freedom of association]].<ref name=\"schimba\"/>, the Constitutional Court heard the case of the Pirate Party leaders and admitted their contestation, overturning the section of the electoral law mandating the number of founding members.<ref name=\"schimba\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gandul.info/stiri/partidul-pirat-din-romania-schimba-legea-partidelor-politice-la-ccr-nu-mai-e-nevoie-de-minimum-25-000-de-membri-fondatori-13899122 |title=Partidul Pirat din Rom\u00e2nia schimb\u0103 legea partidelor politice la CCR: nu mai e nevoie de minimum 25.000 de membri fondatori  |publisher=G\u00e2ndul |accessdate=2015-02-27|language=ro}}</ref>\n\n\n== Party deregistration==\nOfficially, as of March 2020 the party is no longer active as per internal party decisions.\n\n\n==External links==\n* [http://partidulpirat.ro/ Partidul Pirat Romania] official website {{in lang|ro}}\n* [http://blog.partidulpirat.ro/ Blog of Partidul Pirat Romania] {{in lang|ro}}\n* [http://wiki.partidulpirat.ro/ Wiki of Partidul Pirat Romania] {{in lang|ro}}\n* [http://partidulpirat.forum.ro/ Forum of Partidul Pirat Romania] o{{in lang|ro}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Pirate Party}}\n{{Romanian political parties}}\n\n[[Category:Pirate parties|Romania]]\n[[Category:Liberal parties in Romania]]\n[[Category:2009 establishments in Romania]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 2009]]\n\n\n{{Romania-party-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox political party\n| name = Pirate Party Romania\n| native_name = Partidul Pirat Romania\n| logo = Piratpartiet.svg\n| logo_size = 200px\n| colorcode = #0000FF\n| foundation = 2009\n| ideology = [[Pirate Party|Pirate politics]]<br>\n[[Freedom of Information]]<br>\n[[Privacy]]<br>\n[[Distributism]]<br>\n[[Open government|Transparency of government]]\n| international = [[Pirate Parties International]]\n| website = [http://partidulpirat.ro/ www.partidulpirat.ro]\n}}\n\nThe ''' Pirate Party Romania''' ({{lang-ro|Partidul Pirat Rom\u00e2nia}}) is a [[political party]] in [[Romania]] based on the Swedish [[Pirate Party (Sweden)|Pirate Party]].  The party was a member of the [[Pirate Parties International|international Pirate Party movement]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pp-international.net/node/11 |title=PPI Members |publisher=PP-International |accessdate=2009-12-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100529031446/http://www.pp-international.net/node/11 |archivedate=2010-05-29 }}</ref> and is focused on copyright and patent reform, internet freedom, and government transparency.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.capital.ro/articol/update-pachetul-telecom-imposibil-de-implementat-in-forma-sa-actuala-125212.html |title=Telecom Package, impossible to implement in current state  |publisher=Capital |accessdate=2009-12-10|language=ro}}</ref>\n\nThe website of the Romanian Pirate Party was launched on 9 June 2009, and the first online meeting was held on 19 July 2009. The same year, on 6 August, members held their first live meeting, while one month later, on 7 September, the first article regarding the party was published in the Romanian online media.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.realitatea.net/partidul-piratilor-din-romania-se-va-infiinta-in-jumatate-de-an_608577.html |title=Romanian Pirate Party will be established in six months  |publisher=Realitatea TV |accessdate=2009-12-10|language=ro}}</ref>\n\n==Party registration==\n\nIn preparation for the official registration the party statute was approved by the founding members, and the first elected board was composed of Cristian Bulumac (President), \u015etefan Marius Angelescu (Vice-President), Claudiu Marginean (Founding President), \u0218tefan Cristian Br\u00eendu\u0219\u0103 (General Secretary) until March 2020, with a few exceptions.\n\nOn 11 February 2014 the party has submitted to the authorities the official request to be legally registered as a political party without the required signatures of 25,000 founding members.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vice.com/ro/read/piratii-ataca-legea-partidelor-la-curtea-constitutionala |title=Pirates attack the law at the Constitutional Court  |publisher=Vice.com/ro |accessdate=2014-02-14|language=ro}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2015, the Pirate Party contested the electoral law at the [[Constitutional Court of Romania]], arguing that the law violates [[freedom of association]].<ref name=\"schimba\"/>, the Constitutional Court heard the case of the Pirate Party leaders and admitted their contestation, overturning the section of the electoral law mandating the number of founding members.<ref name=\"schimba\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gandul.info/stiri/partidul-pirat-din-romania-schimba-legea-partidelor-politice-la-ccr-nu-mai-e-nevoie-de-minimum-25-000-de-membri-fondatori-13899122 |title=Partidul Pirat din Rom\u00e2nia schimb\u0103 legea partidelor politice la CCR: nu mai e nevoie de minimum 25.000 de membri fondatori  |publisher=G\u00e2ndul |accessdate=2015-02-27|language=ro}}</ref>\n\n\n== Party deregistration==\nOfficially, as of March 2020 the party is no longer active as per internal party decisions.\n\n\n==External links==\n* [http://partidulpirat.ro/ Partidul Pirat Romania] official website {{in lang|ro}}\n* [http://blog.partidulpirat.ro/ Blog of Partidul Pirat Romania] {{in lang|ro}}\n* [http://wiki.partidulpirat.ro/ Wiki of Partidul Pirat Romania] {{in lang|ro}}\n* [http://partidulpirat.forum.ro/ Forum of Partidul Pirat Romania] o{{in lang|ro}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Pirate Party}}\n{{Romanian political parties}}\n\n[[Category:Pirate parties|Romania]]\n[[Category:Liberal parties in Romania]]\n[[Category:2009 establishments in Romania]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 2009]]\n\n\n{{Romania-party-stub}}\n", "name_user": "BlackNoxis", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pirate_Party_Romania"}
{"title_page": "European and Developing Countries Clinical Trials Partnership", "text_new": "{{third-party sources|date=February 2013}}\nThe '''European and Developing Countries Clinical Trials Partnership''' or '''EDCTP''' is a partnership between the [[European Union]] (EU), [[Norway]], [[Switzerland]] and developing countries and other donors, as well as the [[pharmaceutical industry]], to enable [[clinical trials]] and the development of new medicines and [[vaccine]]s against [[HIV|HIV/AIDS]], [[tuberculosis]], and [[malaria]].[http://ec.europa.eu/research/info/conferences/edctp/edctp_en.html] The need for global action against these diseases in order to promote poverty reduction has been recognised by the [[United Nations]], the [[G8]], and the [[African Union]], and the program envisioned the provision of \u20ac600 million for the period 2003\u20132007 in order to translate medical research results into clinical applications relevant to the needs of developing countries.\n\nThe [[European Council]] adopted the '''Programme for Action: Accelerated action on HIV/AIDS, malaria and tuberculosis in the context of poverty reduction''' (COM (2001)96, [http://ec.europa.eu/research/info/conferences/edctp/pdf/com-2001-96_final_en.pdf]) on 15 May 2001, following its launch by the [[European Commission]]. The [[European Commission|Commission]] proposal was adopted on 16 June 2003 by the [[European Council|Council]] and the [[European Parliament]].[http://europa.eu/eur-lex/pri/en/oj/dat/2003/l_169/l_16920030708en00010005.pdf] The Programme was to be based on three central pillars: ''\"...the impact of existing interventions, the affordability of key pharmaceuticals and trade, and the research and development of specific [[global public good]]s.\"''[http://ec.europa.eu/research/info/conferences/edctp/pdf/background_en.pdf] These aims relate specifically with the [[European Union|EU]] stance on access to [[essential medicines]]. [http://ec.europa.eu/comm/trade/issues/global/medecine/index_en.htm]\n\n==Projects and activities==\n\nEDCTP-funded activities are based on:\n\n* North/North networking and co-ordination\n\nPartnerships among the [[European Union|EU]] and associated countries, allowing focused collaboration of national and European efforts that were not previously coordinated.\n\n* North/South networking and co-ordination\n\nPartnerships among [[European Union|EU]] and developing countries that focuses specifically on developing countries' needs, who are jointly involved in setting the research priorities.\n\n* South/South networking and co-ordination\n\nEfforts aimed at creating lasting long-term partnerships between African scientists and research institutions in Africa.\n\n* Supporting relevant clinical trials\n\nAcceleration of the development of new or improved drugs, vaccines and microbicides against HIV/AIDS, malaria and tuberculosis, with a focus on phase II and III clinical trials in sub-Saharan Africa.\n\n* Capacity building\n\nManifested as a general strengthening of clinical research capacity in Africa, including training activities, workshops and meetings, and the upgrading of [[clinical trials|clinical trial]] sites in Africa.\n\n==Funding==\n[[Image:EDCTP proposed expenditure.png|frame|Proposed EDCTP expenditure for the first 5 years of the Programme (2003-2007)[http://ec.europa.eu/research/info/conferences/edctp/pdf/background_en.pdf]]]\n\nThe total budget of the EDCTP is \u20ac600 million for the period 2003\u20132007, of which one third (\u20ac200 million) is to be provided by the [[European Union|EU]] budget, an equivalent amounts from Member States' activities, and the remaining \u20ac200 million from industry, charities, and private organisations. The Partnership is intended to be a long-term initiative (10\u201320 years) and a separate legal entity has been created to maintain its independence and flexibility.\n\nTaken together, clinical trials based in developing countries where the diseases are endemic, capacity building, and South-South networking are expected to make up over 90% of the overall budget. (figure).\n\n==Member states and partners [http://ec.europa.eu/research/info/conferences/edctp/pdf/background_en.pdf]==\n\n* [[Europe]]\n: [[European Union|EU]] member states, plus [[Norway]] and [[Switzerland]] .\n\n* Developing countries\n: All sub-Saharan African countries.\n\n* Industry and commercial\n: [[Bayer]]\n: [[GlaxoSmithKline]]\n: [[Novartis Pharma]]\n: [[Novo Nordisk]]\n: [[Sanofi Pasteur]]\n: [[Sanofi-Aventis]].\n\n* International initiatives\n: [[World Health Organization|The World Health Organization (WHO-TDR)]] (http://www.who.int/tdr/)\n: [[Drugs for Neglected Diseases initiative]] (http://www.dndi.org)\n: International Aids Vaccine Initiative (IAVI) (http://www.iavi.org)\n: European Vaccine Initiative (EVI) (http://www.euvaccine.eu)\n: [[TB Alliance]] (http://www.tballiance.org)\n\n* Private non-profit organisations\n: [[Aeras Global TB Vaccine Foundation]] (https://web.archive.org/web/20090318151237/http://www.aeras.org/home/home.php)\n: [[Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation|The Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation]] (https://web.archive.org/web/20121012112446/http://www.gatesfoundation.org/Pages/home.aspx)\n: [[International Partnership for Microbicides]] (https://web.archive.org/web/20071008192438/http://www.ipm-microbicides.org/)\n: [[Medicines for Malaria Venture]] (https://web.archive.org/web/20090214212631/http://www.mmv.org/index.php)\n: [[Wellcome Trust|The Wellcome Trust]] (http://www.wellcome.ac.uk)\n\n==Representatives==\n\nHigh representative - [[Pascoal Mocumbi]]\n\nExecutive director - [[Charles Mgone]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[European Organisation for Research and Treatment of Cancer]] (EORTC)\n* [[European Medicines Agency]] (EMEA)\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.edctp.org European and Developing Countries Clinical Trials Partnership] (EDCTP)\n\n[[Category:Clinical research]]\n[[Category:International medical and health organizations]]\n[[Category:National agencies for drug regulation]]\n[[Category:Medical and health organisations based in the Netherlands]]\n", "text_old": "{{third-party sources|date=February 2013}}\nThe '''European and Developing Countries Clinical Trials Partnership''' or '''EDCTP''' is a partnership between the [[European Union]] (EU), [[Norway]], [[Switzerland]] and developing countries and other donors, as well as the [[pharmaceutical industry]], to enable [[clinical trials]] and the development of new medicines and [[vaccine]]s against [[HIV|HIV/AIDS]], [[tuberculosis]], and [[malaria]].[http://ec.europa.eu/research/info/conferences/edctp/edctp_en.html] The need for global action against these diseases in order to promote poverty reduction has been recognised by the [[United Nations]], the [[G8]], and the [[African Union]], and the program envisioned the provision of \u20ac600 million for the period 2003-2007 in order to translate medical research results into clinical applications relevant to the needs of developing countries.\n\nThe [[European Council]] adopted the '''Programme for Action: Accelerated action on HIV/AIDS, malaria and tuberculosis in the context of poverty reduction''' (COM (2001)96, [http://ec.europa.eu/research/info/conferences/edctp/pdf/com-2001-96_final_en.pdf]) on 15 May 2001, following its launch by the [[European Commission]]. The [[European Commission|Commission]] proposal was adopted on 16 June 2003 by the [[European Council|Council]] and the [[European Parliament]].[http://europa.eu/eur-lex/pri/en/oj/dat/2003/l_169/l_16920030708en00010005.pdf] The Programme was to be based on three central pillars: ''\"...the impact of existing interventions, the affordability of key pharmaceuticals and trade, and the research and development of specific [[global public good]]s.\"''[http://ec.europa.eu/research/info/conferences/edctp/pdf/background_en.pdf] These aims relate specifically with the [[European Union|EU]] stance on access to [[essential medicines]]. [http://ec.europa.eu/comm/trade/issues/global/medecine/index_en.htm]\n\n==Projects and activities==\n\nEDCTP-funded activities are based on:\n\n* North/North networking and co-ordination\n\nPartnerships among the [[European Union|EU]] and associated countries, allowing focused collaboration of national and European efforts that were not previously coordinated.\n\n* North/South networking and co-ordination\n\nPartnerships among [[European Union|EU]] and developing countries that focuses specifically on developing countries' needs, who are jointly involved in setting the research priorities.\n\n* South/South networking and co-ordination\n\nEfforts aimed at creating lasting long-term partnerships between African scientists and research institutions in Africa.\n\n* Supporting relevant clinical trials\n\nAcceleration of the development of new or improved drugs, vaccines and microbicides against HIV/AIDS, malaria and tuberculosis, with a focus on phase II and III clinical trials in sub-Saharan Africa.\n\n* Capacity building\n\nManifested as a general strengthening of clinical research capacity in Africa, including training activities, workshops and meetings, and the upgrading of [[clinical trials|clinical trial]] sites in Africa.\n\n==Funding==\n[[Image:EDCTP proposed expenditure.png|frame|Proposed EDCTP expenditure for the first 5 years of the Programme (2003-2007)[http://ec.europa.eu/research/info/conferences/edctp/pdf/background_en.pdf]]]\n\nThe total budget of the EDCTP is \u20ac600 million for the period 2003-2007, of which one third (\u20ac200 million) is to be provided by the [[European Union|EU]] budget, an equivalent amounts from Member States' activities, and the remaining \u20ac200 million from industry, charities, and private organisations. The Partnership is intended to be a long-term initiative (10\u201320 years) and a separate legal entity has been created to maintain its independence and flexibility.\n\nTaken together, clinical trials based in developing countries where the diseases are endemic, capacity building, and South-South networking are expected to make up over 90% of the overall budget. (figure).\n\n==Member states and partners [http://ec.europa.eu/research/info/conferences/edctp/pdf/background_en.pdf]==\n\n* [[Europe]]\n: [[European Union|EU]] member states, plus [[Norway]] and [[Switzerland]] .\n\n* Developing countries\n: All sub-Saharan African countries.\n\n* Industry and commercial\n: [[Bayer]]\n: [[GlaxoSmithKline]]\n: [[Novartis Pharma]]\n: [[Novo Nordisk]]\n: [[Sanofi Pasteur]]\n: [[Sanofi-Aventis]].\n\n* International initiatives\n: [[World Health Organization|The World Health Organization (WHO-TDR)]] (http://www.who.int/tdr/)\n: [[Drugs for Neglected Diseases initiative]] (http://www.dndi.org)\n: International Aids Vaccine Initiative (IAVI) (http://www.iavi.org)\n: European Vaccine Initiative (EVI) (http://www.euvaccine.eu)\n: [[TB Alliance]] (http://www.tballiance.org)\n\n* Private non-profit organisations\n: [[Aeras Global TB Vaccine Foundation]] (https://web.archive.org/web/20090318151237/http://www.aeras.org/home/home.php)\n: [[Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation|The Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation]] (https://web.archive.org/web/20121012112446/http://www.gatesfoundation.org/Pages/home.aspx)\n: [[International Partnership for Microbicides]] (https://web.archive.org/web/20071008192438/http://www.ipm-microbicides.org/)\n: [[Medicines for Malaria Venture]] (https://web.archive.org/web/20090214212631/http://www.mmv.org/index.php)\n: [[Wellcome Trust|The Wellcome Trust]] (http://www.wellcome.ac.uk)\n\n==Representatives==\n\nHigh representative - [[Pascoal Mocumbi]]\n\nExecutive director - [[Charles Mgone]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[European Organisation for Research and Treatment of Cancer]] (EORTC)\n* [[European Medicines Agency]] (EMEA)\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.edctp.org European and Developing Countries Clinical Trials Partnership] (EDCTP)\n\n[[Category:Clinical research]]\n[[Category:International medical and health organizations]]\n[[Category:National agencies for drug regulation]]\n[[Category:Medical and health organisations based in the Netherlands]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 2003-2007 \u2192 2003\u20132007, 2003-2007 \u2192 2003\u20132007", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/European_and_Developing_Countries_Clinical_Trials_Partnership"}
{"title_page": "Roses (Saint Jhn song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Roses\n| cover      = \n| alt        =\n| caption    = \n| type       = song\n| artist     = [[Saint Jhn]]\n| album      =\n| released   = {{start date|2016|07|mf=y}}\n| recorded   =\n| genre      = <!-- Please source genres. Any unsourced genres will be removed -->\n| length     = {{duration|m=2|s=53}}\n| label      =\n* Godd Complexx\n* [[Hitco]]\n| writer     =\n* [[Saint Jhn|Carlos St. John Phillips]]\n* Lee Stanshenko\n| producer   = Fallen\n| prev_title = \n| prev_year  = \n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|XHA-QM-q-3E|\"Roses\"}}|type=song}}\n}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Roses (Imanbek Remix)\n| cover      = Saint Jhn - Roses (Imanbek Remix).png\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Imanbek remix cover\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Saint Jhn]]\n| album      =\n| released   = {{start date|2019|06|06|mf=y}}\n| recorded   =\n| genre      = <!-- Please source genres. Any unsourced genres will be removed -->\n| length     = {{duration|m=2|s=56}}\n| label      =\n* Godd Complexx\n* [[Hitco]]\n* Effective\n| writer     =\n* [[Saint Jhn|Carlos St. John Phillips]]\n* Lee Stanshenko\n| producer   =\n* [[Imanbek]]\n* Fallen\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Saint Jhn]]\n | type       = singles\n | prev_title = [[Anything Can Happen (Saint Jhn song)|Anything Can Happen]]\n | prev_year  = 2019\n | title      = Roses\n | year       = 2019\n | next_title = \n | next_year  = \n}}\n{{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Imanbek]]\n | type       = singles\n | prev_title = \n | prev_year  = \n | title      = Roses (Imanbek remix)\n | year       = 2019\n | next_title = Hot by Parah Dice (Imanbek remix)\n | next_year  = 2019\n}}\n}}\n\"'''Roses'''\" is a song by [[Guyanese-American]] rapper [[Saint Jhn]], originally released in July 2016<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/saint-jhn-roses-new-song.1970748.html|title=SAINt JHN \u2013 Roses|website=HotNewHipHop|last=Smith|first=Trevor|date=July 24, 2016|accessdate=January 13, 2020}}</ref> and later included on his 2018 album ''Collection One''. It was then remixed by Kazakh producer [[Imanbek]] and released as a single on September 13, 2019. The remix helped the song gain international recognition.<ref name=\"Caravan\"/> \n\n==Production==\n19-year-old Kazakh musician and producer Imanbek Zeykenov remixed the song and released it as a single in 2019 through the Russian label Effective Records without Saint Jhn's involvement. Zeykenov attempted to contact Saint Jhn on [[Instagram]], but did not receive a reply.<ref name=\"Caravan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.caravan.kz/news/zheleznodorozhnik-iz-aksu-sozdavshijj-vsemirno-izvestnyjj-remiks-na-saint-jhn-roses-kto-on-582304/|title=\u0416\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0437\u043d\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0436\u043d\u0438\u043a \u0438\u0437 \u0410\u043a\u0441\u0443, \u0441\u043e\u0437\u0434\u0430\u0432\u0448\u0438\u0439 \u0432\u0441\u0435\u043c\u0438\u0440\u043d\u043e \u0438\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0440\u0435\u043c\u0438\u043a\u0441 \u043d\u0430 \"SAINt JHN - Roses\": \u043a\u0442\u043e \u043e\u043d|trans-title=Aksu railwayman who created the world famous remix of \"SAINt JHN \u2013 Roses\": who is he|website=Caravan.kz|language=ru|date=October 30, 2019|accessdate=January 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nFollowing the release of the Imanbek remix, \"Roses\" went on to gain success in many countries across the globe, reaching number one in both Australia<ref name=\"AUS\" /> and Ireland<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/saint-jhn-claims-first-number-1-on-the-official-irish-singles-chart-with-roses-lady-gagas-stupid-love-is-highest-new-entry__28979/|title=Saint Jhn claims first Number 1 on the Official Irish Singles Chart with Roses, Lady Gaga's Stupid Love is highest new entry|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|last=White|first=Jack|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref> and spending two weeks at number one on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/saint-jhn-holds-on-to-number-1-for-a-second-week-with-roses__29225/|title=Saint Jhn holds on to Number 1 for a second week with Roses|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|last=Ainsley|first=Helen|date=March 27, 2020|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Charts==\n===Original or combined version===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2019\u20132020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Australia ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref name=\"AUS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/charts/singles-chart|title=ARIA Australian Top 50 Singles|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|date=April 6, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Canada ([[Canadian Hot 100]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/canadian-hot-100/2020-04-11|title=Canadian Hot 100: April 11, 2020|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n| 6\n|-\n{{single chart|Czechdigital|1|year=2020|week=14|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Denmark ([[Tracklisten]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitlisten.nu/default.asp?w=12&y=2020&list=t40|title=Track Top-40 Uge 12, 2020|publisher=[[Hitlisten]]|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n| 3\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| France ([[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|SNEP]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://snepmusique.com/les-tops/le-top-de-la-semaine/top-albums/?semaine=14?&annee=2020&categorie=Top%20Singles|title=Top Singles (Week 14, 2020)|publisher=[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique]]|language=French|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n| 8\n|-\n{{single chart|Ireland4|1|date=20200306|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 7, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Portugal|46|artist=Saint Jhn|song=Roses|rowheader=