{"title_page": "Hendrik van der Veen", "text_new": "'''Hendrik van der Veen''' (1888\u20131977)<ref name=bio>[http://www.biografischportaal.nl/persoon/30826446 Hendrik van der Veen] at biografischportaal.nl <!--needs a better description, but right now the server is down--></ref> was a [[Dutch people|Dutch]] missionary worker and linguist who worked in [[Tana Toraja]], [[Dutch East Indies]].\n\nVan der Veen was born on 21 July 1888 in [[Rossum, Gelderland|Rossum]], [[Bommelerwaard]], as the son of the pastor Jan van der Veen. He initially aimed to work as a linguist in [[Halmahera]], but was sent to Tana Toraja at the suggestion of missionary [[Antonie Aris van de Loosdrecht]].\n\nThe Biblical Institute of the Netherlands issued instructions to Dr. Hendrik van der Veen on June 9, 1916: his main task was the translation of the [[Bible]], in accordance with his expertise as a linguist.<ref name=\"Th. van den End\">{{cite book |last=van den End |first=Th. |date=1994 |title=Sumber-sumber Zending tentang Sejarah Gereja Toraja 1901-1961 |trans-title=Mission Resources on the History of the Toraja Church 1901-1961 |language=Indonesian |location=Jakarta |publisher=BPK Gunung Mulia |page= 104 }}</ref>\n\nIn May 1916, he left for [[Batavia, Dutch East Indies|Batavia]] and stayed for three months. At the end of August, he arrived at [[Makassar]], boarding the ship to [[Palopo]] and then to [[Rantepao]].<ref name=\"Th. van den End\"/> Hendrik van der Veen arrived in Rantepao, Tana Toraja, on 11 September 1916, and was greeted by the family of van de Loosdrecht and [[Johannes Belksma]]. Van der Veen remained in Indonesia after its independence from the Netherlands in 1948 until ca. 1960, after which he returned to the Netherlands. On October 19, 1977, he died in [[Leusden]] at the age of 89.<ref name=bio/>\n\n==Hendrik van der Veen's Work in Tana Toraja==\nWhile in Tana Toraja, Van der Veen compiled biblical books for local schools, and began translating the [[Gospel of Luke]] into the [[Toraja-Sa\u2019dan language|Toraja language]].<ref name=\"Daniel Pasally Gasong\">{{cite book |last=Gasong |first=Daniel Pasally |date=1991 |title=Rapih Tersusun: Suatu Tinjauan Teologis tentang Pertumbuhan Jemaat Misioner dalam Gereja Toraja |trans-title=Neatly Preapred: A Theological Review of the Growth of a Missionary Congregation in the Toraja Church |language=Indonesian |location=Jakarta |publisher=STT Jakarta |pages= 22\u201327}}</ref> This book became the first part of his translation of the [[New Testament]], intended for use in Christmas meetings. Van der Veen also compiled a Toraja-Dutch dictionary, published in 1940; translated the [[Old Testament]] from 1947\u20131955; completed the entire translation of the Old Testament and the New Testament into the Toraja language, eventually known as ''Sura Madatu'', and published in 1960; and began work on a Toraja-Indonesian dictionary. This dictionary was not completed by van der Veen, and ultimately continued by J. Tammu and L. Pakan.<ref name = \"Daniel Pasally Gasong\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Veen, hendrik van der}}\n[[Category:1888 births]]\n[[Category:1977 deaths]]\n[[Category:Dutch expatriates in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Dutch Protestant missionaries]]\n[[Category:Linguists from the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Linguists of Austronesian languages]]\n[[Category:Linguists of Papuan languages]]\n[[Category:Linguists of West Papuan languages]]\n[[Category:Missionary linguists]]\n[[Category:People from Maasdriel]]\n[[Category:Protestant missionaries in Indonesia]]\n", "text_old": "'''Hendrik van der Veen''' (1888\u20131977)<ref name=bio>[http://www.biografischportaal.nl/persoon/30826446 Hendrik van der Veen] at biografischportaal.nl <!--needs a better description, but right now the server is down--></ref> was a [[Dutch people|Dutch]] missionary worker and linguist who worked in [[Tana Toraja]], [[Dutch East Indies]]. \n\nVan der Veen was born on 21 July 1888 in [[Rossum, Gelderland|Rossum]], [[Bommelerwaard]], as the son of the pastor Jan van der Veen. He initially aimed to work as a linguist in [[Halmahera]], but was sent to Tana Toraja at the suggestion of missionary [[Antonie Aris van de Loosdrecht]]. \n\nThe Biblical Institute of the Netherlands issued instructions to Dr. Hendrik van der Veen on June 9, 1916: his main task was the translation of the [[Bible]], in accordance with his expertise as a linguist.<ref name=\"Th. van den End\">{{cite book |last=van den End |first=Th. |date=1994 |title=Sumber-sumber Zending tentang Sejarah Gereja Toraja 1901-1961 |trans-title=Mission Resources on the History of the Toraja Church 1901-1961 |language=Indonesian |location=Jakarta |publisher=BPK Gunung Mulia |page= 104 }}</ref> \n\nIn May 1916, he left for [[Batavia, Dutch East Indies|Batavia]] and stayed for three months. At the end of August, he arrived at [[Makassar]], boarding the ship to [[Palopo]] and then to [[Rantepao]].<ref name=\"Th. van den End\"/> Hendrik van der Veen arrived in Rantepao, Tana Toraja, on 11 September 1916, and was greeted by the family of van de Loosdrecht and [[Johannes Belksma]]. Van der Veen remained in Indonesia after its independence from the Netherlands in 1948 until ca. 1960, after which he returned to the Netherlands. On October 19, 1977, he died in [[Leusden]] at the age of 89.<ref name=bio/>\n\n==Hendrik van der Veen's Work in Tana Toraja==\nWhile in Tana Toraja, Van der Veen compiled biblical books for local schools, and began translating the [[Gospel of Luke]] into the [[Toraja-Sa\u2019dan language|Toraja language]].<ref name=\"Daniel Pasally Gasong\"> {{cite book |last=Gasong |first=Daniel Pasally |date=1991 |title=Rapih Tersusun: Suatu Tinjauan Teologis tentang Pertumbuhan Jemaat Misioner dalam Gereja Toraja |trans-title=Neatly Preapred: A Theological Review of the Growth of a Missionary Congregation in the Toraja Church |language=Indonesian |location=Jakarta |publisher=STT Jakarta |page= 22\u201327}}</ref> This book became the first part of his translation of the [[New Testament]], intended for use in Christmas meetings. Van der Veen also compiled a Toraja-Dutch dictionary, published in 1940; translated the [[Old Testament]] from 1947\u20131955; completed the entire translation of the Old Testament and the New Testament into the Toraja language, eventually known as ''Sura Madatu'', and published in 1960; and began work on a Toraja-Indonesian dictionary. This dictionary was not completed by van der Veen, and ultimately continued by J. Tammu and L. Pakan.<ref name = \"Daniel Pasally Gasong\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Veen, hendrik van der}}\n[[Category:1888 births]]\n[[Category:1977 deaths]]\n[[Category:Dutch expatriates in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Dutch Protestant missionaries]]\n[[Category:Linguists from the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Linguists of Austronesian languages]]\n[[Category:Linguists of Papuan languages]]\n[[Category:Linguists of West Papuan languages]]\n[[Category:Missionary linguists]]\n[[Category:People from Maasdriel]]\n[[Category:Protestant missionaries in Indonesia]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hendrik_van_der_Veen"}
{"title_page": "Masanobu Tsuji", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= Masanobu Tsuji\n|birth_date=October 11, 1901\n|death_date= [[Declared death in absentia|Declared dead]] 20 July 1968 (age 60-67)\n|birth_place= [[Ishikawa Prefecture]], [[Japan]]\n|death_place=Unknown\n|image=Tuji Masanobu.jpg\n|caption= \n|nickname=\n|allegiance={{Flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|branch={{Army|Empire of Japan}}\n|serviceyears= 1924\u20131945\n|rank= [[Colonel]] [[File:\u5e1d\u570b\u9678\u8ecd\u306e\u968e\u7d1a\u2015\u80a9\u7ae0\u2015\u5927\u4f50.svg|35px]] \n|commands= \n|unit=\n|battles= [[World War II]] ([[Pacific War]])\n|awards=\n|laterwork=\n}}\n[[File:Memorial statue of Masanobu Tsuji.JPG|thumb|Memorial statue of Masanobu Tsuji in [[Kaga, Ishikawa]]]]\n\n{{Japanese name|Tsuji}}\n{{nihongo|'''Masanobu Tsuji '''|\u8fbb \u653f\u4fe1|Tsuji Masanobu|11 October 1901 &ndash; ca.1961<ref>Tsuji's birthyear is disputed.  Several Japanese sources use 1903, but Tsuji himself wrote it was 1901. Other sources say 1900 or 1902. The 1901 date is from David Bergamini's ''Japan's Imperial Conspiracy'', p. 981.</ref>}} was a Japanese army officer and politician. During [[World War II]], he was an important tactical planner in the [[Imperial Japanese Army]]; he developed the detailed plans for [[Malayan Campaign|the successful Japanese invasion of Malaya]] at the start of the war.<ref>[[John Toland (author)|John Toland]], ''[[The Rising Sun]]'', page 183</ref> He also helped plan and lead the final Japanese offensive during the [[Guadalcanal Campaign]].\n\nTsuji was deeply involved in Japanese atrocities throughout the war, including [[Bataan Death March]] and [[Sook Ching]]. He evaded prosecution for war crimes at the end of the war, living in hiding in [[Thailand]]. He returned to Japan in 1949 and was elected to the [[Diet of Japan|Diet]] as an advocate of renewed militarism. In 1961, he disappeared on a trip to [[Laos]].<ref name=\"KGB\">{{cite web|url=http://pwencycl.kgbudge.com/T/s/Tsuji_Masanobu.htm| title=Tsuji Masanobu|publisher=The Pacific War Online Encyclopedia|accessdate=April 28, 2012|author=Budge, Kent G.}}</ref>\n\nTsuji was among the most aggressive and influential Japanese militarists. He was a leading proponent of the concept of ''[[gekokuj\u014d]]'', \"leading from below\" or \"loyal insubordination\" by acting without or contrary to authorization.<ref name=\"KGB\"/> He incited the [[Nomonhan Incident|1939 border clash with the USSR]] and was a vehement advocate of war with the [[United States]].<ref name=\"thediplomat.com\">{{cite news|first=Stuart|last=Goldman|url=http://thediplomat.com/2012/08/the-forgotten-soviet-japanese-war-of-1939/?allpages=yes|title=The Forgotten Soviet-Japanese War of 1939|work=[[The Diplomat]]|date=August 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nMasunobu Tsuji was born in the [[Ishikawa Prefecture]] in Japan. He received his secondary education at a military academy and then graduated from the War College.\n\nBy 1934, he was active in the Army's political intrigues as a member of the ''T\u014dseiha''\n(\"[[Control Faction]]\"), and helped block the attempted coup d'\u00e9tat of the rival ''K\u014dd\u014dha'' (\"[[Imperial Way Faction]]\"). This brought him the patronage of general and future Prime Minister [[Hideki Tojo]] and general and future War Minister [[Seishir\u014d Itagaki]].<ref name=\"KGB\"/>\n\n==Atrocities and War Crimes==\nWhen the war with America and Britain started, Tsuji was on the staff of General [[Tomoyuki Yamashita]], whose army invaded [[British Malaya|Malaya]].<ref name=\"DF\">Dan Ford, Warbird Forum [http://www.warbirdforum.com/tsuji.htm \"Colonel Tsuji of Malaya\"]</ref> He was largely responsible for planning Yamashita's successful landing in Malaya and subsequent campaign against [[Singapore]].<ref>Bergamini, p. 981.</ref> After the capture of Singapore, Tsuji helped plan the ''[[Sook Ching]]'' - a systematic massacre of thousands of Malayan Chinese who might be hostile to Japan.<ref>Yoji, Akashi; Mako, Yoshimura (eds.) ''New Perspectives on the Japanese Occupation in Malaya and Singapore'' Hayashii, Hirofumi. [http://www.geocities.jp/hhhirofumi/eng18.htm Chapter 9. Massacre of Chinese in Singapore and Its Coverage in Postwar Japan] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170110144706/http://www.geocities.jp/hhhirofumi/eng18.htm |date=2017-01-10 }} Singapore: National University of Singapore Press, 2008</ref> \n\nHe was then transferred to the staff of [[Masaharu Homma|General Homma]] in the [[Philippines]]. After the U.S. surrender there, Tsuji sought to have all [[American]] prisoners killed, and encouraged the brutal mistreatment and casual murder of prisoners in the [[Bataan Death March]].<ref name=\"us-japandialogueonpows.org\">{{cite web|title= The Causes of the Bataan Death March Revisited |url= http://www.us-japandialogueonpows.org/Nelson.htm}}</ref> He also had many captured officials of the Philippines government executed, including ordering the execution of [[Filipino]] Chief Justice [[Jos\u00e9 Abad Santos]] and attempted execution of former Speaker of the House of Representatives [[Manuel Roxas]]\n\n==War Criminal==\nAfter the war, the Japanese war criminals were prosecuted, but Tsuji fled and was able to avoid the [[Sook Ching]] trial. Some other army officials, for following Tsuji's command, were charged with conducting the [[Sook Ching]], and two of them were executed. Because of the war crimes at the [[Bataan Death March]],<ref name=\"us-japandialogueonpows.org\">{{cite web|title= The Causes of the Bataan Death March Revisited |url= http://www.us-japandialogueonpows.org/Nelson.htm}}</ref> [[Masaharu Homma|General Homma]], who considered himself a humanist and was surprised to hear the facts of Bataan death march after the war, was held responsible for his subordinates and was executed while Tsuji was on the run.\n\n==Others==\nIn 1932, he saw action in China, and subsequently travelled as far as Sinkiang.<ref name=\"DF\"/>\nTsuji served as a staff officer in the [[Kwantung Army]] in 1937-1939. His aggressive and insubordinate attitude exacerbated the [[Soviet\u2013Japanese border conflicts]], and helped incite to the [[Battle of Khalkhin Gol]] in 1939.<ref name=\"Coox\">[[Alvin Coox|Coox, Alvin D.]] ''Nomonhan: Japan Against Russia, 1939'', {{ISBN|0-8047-1835-0}}</ref>\n\nAfter the defeat at Khalkhin Gol, Tsuji opposed any further conflicts with the USSR. After their attack on the USSR in 1941, the Germans urged the Japanese to join the invasion, and many in the Japanese military wanted to avenge the defeat at Khalkhin Gol. Yet Tsuji was an influential advocate of the attack on the United States. General [[Ry\u016bkichi Tanaka|Ryukichi Tanaka]] testified after the war that, \"the most determined single protagonist in favor of war with the United States was Tsuji Masanobu.\" Tsuji later wrote that his experience of Soviet fire-power at Khalkhin Gol convinced him not to attack the Soviet Union in 1941.<ref name=\"thediplomat.com\">{{cite news|first=Stuart|last=Goldman|url=http://thediplomat.com/2012/08/the-forgotten-soviet-japanese-war-of-1939/?allpages=yes|title=The Forgotten Soviet-Japanese War of 1939|work=[[The Diplomat]]|date=August 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\nHis protectors in the Army got him safely transferred to [[Taiwan]], where he helped organize the Army's jungle warfare school. He was then assigned to the Operations Section of the General staff, where he became a strong advocate of war with the United States and [[United Kingdom|Britain]]. It has been alleged that in late 1941, he planned the assassination of [[Fumimaro Konoe|Prime Minister Konoye]], if Konoye achieved peace with the U.S.<ref name=\"KGB\"/>\n\nTsuji planned the Japanese overland attack in [[New Guinea]], via the [[Kokoda Trail]]. In this as in other operations, he ordered bold offensive moves regardless of difficulties or the costs to the troops involved.\n\nIn late 1942, Tsuji went to Guadalcanal, where he planned and led the last major Japanese attack on October 23\u201324. After these attacks were defeated, Tsuji went to Tokyo in person to urge additional reinforcements. But he then accepted the Navy's conclusion that nothing could get through, and recommended the evacuation of the remaining troops. He impressed the Emperor with his frankness.\n\nBut the Guadalcanal fiasco had discredited him. He was sent to the Japanese HQ in [[Nanking]], which was largely inactive, for the next year. While there, he made contacts with various Chinese, including both collaborators and agents of [[Chiang Kai-shek]]'s government.<ref name=\"DF\"/>\n\nIn mid-1944, Tsuji was sent to Burma, where Japanese forces [[Battle of Imphal|had been repulsed at Imphal]]. Tsuji was assigned to the 33rd Army, which faced the Chinese in northeastern Burma. He was an energetic and efficient planner, if notoriously arrogant, and once helped quell panic in the ranks by ostentiously having a bath under fire in the front lines.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}\n\nWhen the Japanese position in Burma collapsed in 1945, Tsuji escaped, first to Thailand, and then to China, where he renewed the contacts made in Nanking. He also visited [[Vietnam]], then in disorder with the [[Viet Minh]] resisting the re-establishment of French rule. In China, Tsuji was both a prisoner and an employee of Chinese intelligence.<ref name=\"DF\"/>\n\nIn 1948, he was allowed to resign from Chinese service and returned to Japan. He began publishing books and articles about his war experiences, including an account of the Japanese victory in Malaya. He also wrote of his years in hiding in ''Senk\u014d Sanzenri'' (\u6f5c\u884c\u4e09\u5343\u91cc;) \"3,000 ''[[Li (unit)|li]]'' (Chinese miles) in hiding\", which became a best seller. He was elected to the [[Diet of Japan|Diet]] in 1952, and re-elected twice.<ref name=\"DF\"/>\n\n==Disappearance==\nIn April 1961, he traveled to [[Laos]] and was never heard from again. He may have been killed in the [[Laotian Civil War]], but there were also rumors that he became an adviser to the [[North Vietnam]]ese government. He was declared dead on July 20, 1968.<ref>http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20000726b1.html</ref>\n\nHe held strong \"pan-Asian\" views and thought that the people of other Asian countries should support Japan against Western powers. \nHis ultra-nationalist and militarist views and his war record won him the support of many like-minded Japanese nationalists, to the end of which his supporters erected a statue of him in [[Kaga, Ishikawa|Kaga]] City, Japan.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of people who disappeared mysteriously: pre-1970|List of people who disappeared]]\n\n==Honors==\n* [[Order of the Sacred Treasure]], 3rd Class<ref name=\"t108\">Tsuji, Masanobu. (1997). ''Japan's Greatest Victory, Britain's Worst Defeat,'' p. 108.</ref>\n* [[Order of the Golden Kite]], 4th Class and 5th Class<ref name=\"t108\"/>\n* [[Order of the Rising Sun|Order of the Rising Sun, Gold Rays with Rosette]]<ref name=\"t108\"/>\n* Decoration of [[Manchuria]], 4th Class and 5th Class<ref name=\"t108\"/>\n* Commemoration Medal of the Coronation of [[Emperor Showa]]<ref name=\"t108\"/>\n* [[Commemoration Medal of the Census]]<ref name=\"t108\"/>\n* [[Commemoration Medal of the Founding of Manchuria]]<ref name=\"t108\"/>\n* Commemoration Medal of the 2,600th Year after the Accession of [[Emperor Jimmu]]<ref name=\"t108\"/>\n* [[Campaign Medal of the Chinese Incident]]<ref name=\"t108\"/>\n* Campaign Medal of the [[Manchurian Incident]]<ref name=\"t108\"/>\n\n==Further reading==\n* Peterson, James W., Barry C. Weaver and Michael A. Quigley. (2001). ''Orders and Medals of Japan and Associated States.'' San Ramon, California: Orders and Medals Society of America. {{ISBN|1-890974-09-9}}\n* Tsuji, Masanobu. (1997). ''Japan's Greatest Victory, Britain's Worst Defeat'' (Margaret E. Lake, tr.). New York: [[Da Capo Press]]. {{ISBN|978-1-873376-75-1}} (cloth)\n* Ward, Ian. (1992). \"The Killer They Called a God\" (MediaMaster). {{ISBN|978-9810039219}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://warbirdforum.com/tsuji.htm Colonel Masanobu Tsuji of Malaya]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tsuji, Masanobu}}\n[[Category:1901 births]]\n[[Category:1960s deaths]]\n[[Category:1960s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:Bataan Death March]]\n[[Category:Japanese military leaders]]\n[[Category:Japanese military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Councillors (Japan)]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Representatives (Japan)]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Ishikawa Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Missing person cases in Japan]]\n[[Category:Missing person cases in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Year of death unknown]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Ishikawa Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Rising Sun, 4th class]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Sacred Treasure]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= Masanobu Tsuji\n|birth_date=October 11, 1901\n|death_date= [[Declared death in absentia|Declared dead]] 20 July 1968 (age 60-67)\n|birth_place= [[Ishikawa Prefecture]], [[Japan]]\n|death_place=Unknown\n|image=Tuji Masanobu.jpg\n|caption= \n|nickname=\n|allegiance={{Flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|branch={{Army|Empire of Japan}}\n|serviceyears= 1924\u20131945\n|rank= [[Colonel]] [[File:\u5e1d\u570b\u9678\u8ecd\u306e\u968e\u7d1a\u2015\u80a9\u7ae0\u2015\u5927\u4f50.svg|35px]] \n|commands= \n|unit=\n|battles= [[World War II]] ([[Pacific War]])\n|awards=\n|laterwork=\n}}\n[[File:Memorial statue of Masanobu Tsuji.JPG|thumb|Memorial statue of Masanobu Tsuji in [[Kaga, Ishikawa]]]]\n\n{{Japanese name|Tsuji}}\n{{nihongo|'''Masanobu Tsuji '''|\u8fbb \u653f\u4fe1|Tsuji Masanobu|11 October 1901 &ndash; ca.1961<ref>Tsuji's birthyear is disputed.  Several Japanese sources use 1903, but Tsuji himself wrote it was 1901. Other sources say 1900 or 1902. The 1901 date is from David Bergamini's ''Japan's Imperial Conspiracy'', p. 981.</ref>}} was a Japanese army officer and politician. During [[World War II]], he was an important tactical planner in the [[Imperial Japanese Army]]; he developed the detailed plans for [[Malayan Campaign|the successful Japanese invasion of Malaya]] at the start of the war.<ref>[[John Toland (author)|John Toland]], ''[[The Rising Sun]]'', page 183</ref> He also helped plan and lead the final Japanese offensive during the [[Guadalcanal Campaign]].\n\nTsuji was deeply involved in Japanese atrocities throughout the war, including [[Bataan Death March]] and [[Sook Ching]]. He evaded prosecution for war crimes at the end of the war, living in hiding in [[Thailand]]. He returned to Japan in 1949 and was elected to the [[Diet of Japan|Diet]] as an advocate of renewed militarism. In 1961, he disappeared on a trip to [[Laos]].<ref name=\"KGB\">{{cite web|url=http://pwencycl.kgbudge.com/T/s/Tsuji_Masanobu.htm| title=Tsuji Masanobu|publisher=The Pacific War Online Encyclopedia|accessdate=April 28, 2012|author=Budge, Kent G.}}</ref>\n\nTsuji was among the most aggressive and influential Japanese militarists. He was a leading proponent of the concept of ''[[gekokuj\u014d]]'', \"leading from below\" or \"loyal insubordination\" by acting without or contrary to authorization.<ref name=\"KGB\"/> He incited the [[Nomonhan Incident|1939 border clash with the USSR]] and was a vehement advocate of war with the [[United States]].<ref name=\"thediplomat.com\">{{cite news|first=Stuart|last=Goldman|url=http://thediplomat.com/2012/08/the-forgotten-soviet-japanese-war-of-1939/?allpages=yes|title=The Forgotten Soviet-Japanese War of 1939|work=[[The Diplomat]]|date=August 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nMasunobu Tsuji was born in the [[Ishikawa Prefecture]] in Japan. He received his secondary education at a military academy and then graduated from the War College.\n\nBy 1934, he was active in the Army's political intrigues as a member of the ''T\u014dseiha''\n(\"[[Control Faction]]\"), and helped block the attempted coup d'\u00e9tat of the rival ''K\u014dd\u014dha'' (\"[[Imperial Way Faction]]\"). This brought him the patronage of general and future Prime Minister [[Hideki Tojo]] and general and future War Minister [[Seishir\u014d Itagaki]].<ref name=\"KGB\"/>\n\n==Atrocities and War Crimes==\nWhen the war with America and Britain started, Tsuji was on the staff of General [[Tomoyuki Yamashita]], whose army invaded [[British Malaya|Malaya]].<ref name=\"DF\">Dan Ford, Warbird Forum [http://www.warbirdforum.com/tsuji.htm \"Colonel Tsuji of Malaya\"]</ref> He was largely responsible for planning Yamashita's successful landing in Malaya and subsequent campaign against [[Singapore]].<ref>Bergamini, p. 981.</ref> After the capture of Singapore, Tsuji helped plan the ''[[Sook Ching]]'' - a systematic massacre of thousands of Malayan Chinese who might be hostile to Japan.<ref>Yoji, Akashi; Mako, Yoshimura (eds.) ''New Perspectives on the Japanese Occupation in Malaya and Singapore'' Hayashii, Hirofumi. [http://www.geocities.jp/hhhirofumi/eng18.htm Chapter 9. Massacre of Chinese in Singapore and Its Coverage in Postwar Japan] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170110144706/http://www.geocities.jp/hhhirofumi/eng18.htm |date=2017-01-10 }} Singapore: National University of Singapore Press, 2008</ref> \n\nHe was then transferred to the staff of [[Masaharu Homma|General Homma]] in the [[Philippines]]. After the U.S. surrender there, Tsuji sought to have all American prisoners killed, and encouraged the brutal mistreatment and casual murder of prisoners in the [[Bataan Death March]].<ref name=\"us-japandialogueonpows.org\">{{cite web|title= The Causes of the Bataan Death March Revisited |url= http://www.us-japandialogueonpows.org/Nelson.htm}}</ref> He also had many captured officials of the Philippines government executed, including ordering the execution of Filipino Chief Justice [[Jos\u00e9 Abad Santos]] and attempted execution of former Speaker of the House of Representatives [[Manuel Roxas]]\n\n==War Criminal==\nAfter the war, the Japanese war criminals were prosecuted, but Tsuji fled and was able to avoid the [[Sook Ching]] trial. Some other army officials, for following Tsuji's command, were charged with conducting the [[Sook Ching]], and two of them were executed. Because of the war crimes at the [[Bataan Death March]],<ref name=\"us-japandialogueonpows.org\">{{cite web|title= The Causes of the Bataan Death March Revisited |url= http://www.us-japandialogueonpows.org/Nelson.htm}}</ref> [[Masaharu Homma|General Homma]], who considered himself a humanist and was surprised to hear the facts of Bataan death march after the war, was held responsible for his subordinates and was executed while Tsuji was on the run.\n\n==Others==\nIn 1932, he saw action in China, and subsequently travelled as far as Sinkiang.<ref name=\"DF\"/>\nTsuji served as a staff officer in the [[Kwantung Army]] in 1937-1939. His aggressive and insubordinate attitude exacerbated the [[Soviet\u2013Japanese border conflicts]], and helped incite to the [[Battle of Khalkhin Gol]] in 1939.<ref name=\"Coox\">[[Alvin Coox|Coox, Alvin D.]] ''Nomonhan: Japan Against Russia, 1939'', {{ISBN|0-8047-1835-0}}</ref>\n\nAfter the defeat at Khalkhin Gol, Tsuji opposed any further conflicts with the USSR. After their attack on the USSR in 1941, the Germans urged the Japanese to join the invasion, and many in the Japanese military wanted to avenge the defeat at Khalkhin Gol. Yet Tsuji was an influential advocate of the attack on the United States. General [[Ry\u016bkichi Tanaka|Ryukichi Tanaka]] testified after the war that, \"the most determined single protagonist in favor of war with the United States was Tsuji Masanobu.\" Tsuji later wrote that his experience of Soviet fire-power at Khalkhin Gol convinced him not to attack the Soviet Union in 1941.<ref name=\"thediplomat.com\">{{cite news|first=Stuart|last=Goldman|url=http://thediplomat.com/2012/08/the-forgotten-soviet-japanese-war-of-1939/?allpages=yes|title=The Forgotten Soviet-Japanese War of 1939|work=[[The Diplomat]]|date=August 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\nHis protectors in the Army got him safely transferred to [[Taiwan]], where he helped organize the Army's jungle warfare school. He was then assigned to the Operations Section of the General staff, where he became a strong advocate of war with the United States and [[United Kingdom|Britain]]. It has been alleged that in late 1941, he planned the assassination of [[Fumimaro Konoe|Prime Minister Konoye]], if Konoye achieved peace with the U.S.<ref name=\"KGB\"/>\n\nTsuji planned the Japanese overland attack in [[New Guinea]], via the [[Kokoda Trail]]. In this as in other operations, he ordered bold offensive moves regardless of difficulties or the costs to the troops involved.\n\nIn late 1942, Tsuji went to Guadalcanal, where he planned and led the last major Japanese attack on October 23\u201324. After these attacks were defeated, Tsuji went to Tokyo in person to urge additional reinforcements. But he then accepted the Navy's conclusion that nothing could get through, and recommended the evacuation of the remaining troops. He impressed the Emperor with his frankness.\n\nBut the Guadalcanal fiasco had discredited him. He was sent to the Japanese HQ in [[Nanking]], which was largely inactive, for the next year. While there, he made contacts with various Chinese, including both collaborators and agents of [[Chiang Kai-shek]]'s government.<ref name=\"DF\"/>\n\nIn mid-1944, Tsuji was sent to Burma, where Japanese forces [[Battle of Imphal|had been repulsed at Imphal]]. Tsuji was assigned to the 33rd Army, which faced the Chinese in northeastern Burma. He was an energetic and efficient planner, if notoriously arrogant, and once helped quell panic in the ranks by ostentiously having a bath under fire in the front lines.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}\n\nWhen the Japanese position in Burma collapsed in 1945, Tsuji escaped, first to Thailand, and then to China, where he renewed the contacts made in Nanking. He also visited [[Vietnam]], then in disorder with the [[Viet Minh]] resisting the re-establishment of French rule. In China, Tsuji was both a prisoner and an employee of Chinese intelligence.<ref name=\"DF\"/>\n\nIn 1948, he was allowed to resign from Chinese service and returned to Japan. He began publishing books and articles about his war experiences, including an account of the Japanese victory in Malaya. He also wrote of his years in hiding in ''Senk\u014d Sanzenri'' (\u6f5c\u884c\u4e09\u5343\u91cc;) \"3,000 ''[[Li (unit)|li]]'' (Chinese miles) in hiding\", which became a best seller. He was elected to the [[Diet of Japan|Diet]] in 1952, and re-elected twice.<ref name=\"DF\"/>\n\n==Disappearance==\nIn April 1961, he traveled to [[Laos]] and was never heard from again. He may have been killed in the [[Laotian Civil War]], but there were also rumors that he became an adviser to the [[North Vietnam]]ese government. He was declared dead on July 20, 1968.<ref>http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20000726b1.html</ref>\n\nHe held strong \"pan-Asian\" views and thought that the people of other Asian countries should support Japan against Western powers. \nHis ultra-nationalist and militarist views and his war record won him the support of many like-minded Japanese nationalists, to the end of which his supporters erected a statue of him in [[Kaga, Ishikawa|Kaga]] City, Japan.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of people who disappeared mysteriously: pre-1970|List of people who disappeared]]\n\n==Honors==\n* [[Order of the Sacred Treasure]], 3rd Class<ref name=\"t108\">Tsuji, Masanobu. (1997). ''Japan's Greatest Victory, Britain's Worst Defeat,'' p. 108.</ref>\n* [[Order of the Golden Kite]], 4th Class and 5th Class<ref name=\"t108\"/>\n* [[Order of the Rising Sun|Order of the Rising Sun, Gold Rays with Rosette]]<ref name=\"t108\"/>\n* Decoration of [[Manchuria]], 4th Class and 5th Class<ref name=\"t108\"/>\n* Commemoration Medal of the Coronation of [[Emperor Showa]]<ref name=\"t108\"/>\n* [[Commemoration Medal of the Census]]<ref name=\"t108\"/>\n* [[Commemoration Medal of the Founding of Manchuria]]<ref name=\"t108\"/>\n* Commemoration Medal of the 2,600th Year after the Accession of [[Emperor Jimmu]]<ref name=\"t108\"/>\n* [[Campaign Medal of the Chinese Incident]]<ref name=\"t108\"/>\n* Campaign Medal of the [[Manchurian Incident]]<ref name=\"t108\"/>\n\n==Further reading==\n* Peterson, James W., Barry C. Weaver and Michael A. Quigley. (2001). ''Orders and Medals of Japan and Associated States.'' San Ramon, California: Orders and Medals Society of America. {{ISBN|1-890974-09-9}}\n* Tsuji, Masanobu. (1997). ''Japan's Greatest Victory, Britain's Worst Defeat'' (Margaret E. Lake, tr.). New York: [[Da Capo Press]]. {{ISBN|978-1-873376-75-1}} (cloth)\n* Ward, Ian. (1992). \"The Killer They Called a God\" (MediaMaster). {{ISBN|978-9810039219}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://warbirdforum.com/tsuji.htm Colonel Masanobu Tsuji of Malaya]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tsuji, Masanobu}}\n[[Category:1901 births]]\n[[Category:1960s deaths]]\n[[Category:1960s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:Bataan Death March]]\n[[Category:Japanese military leaders]]\n[[Category:Japanese military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Councillors (Japan)]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Representatives (Japan)]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Ishikawa Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Missing person cases in Japan]]\n[[Category:Missing person cases in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Year of death unknown]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Ishikawa Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Rising Sun, 4th class]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Sacred Treasure]]\n", "name_user": "Juanmakabulos", "label": "safe", "comment":